  "prompt": "Are there legal frameworks in place to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several legal frameworks designed to combat money laundering at national and international levels. Some key examples include:\n\n1. International Frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n\n2. United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act (AMLA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n3. European Union:\n- Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- 5th and 6th Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Intelligence Unit regulations\n\n4. National Regulations:\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious Transaction Reporting\n- Customer due diligence procedures\n- Enhanced monitoring of high-risk transactions\n\nThese frameworks typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious activities\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement robust internal control systems\n- Conduct regular risk assessments\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant financial fines and potential criminal prosecution.",
